Cell[BoxData["\<\"Mathematica note: In \[GothicCapitalD](r), above, \
Mathematica code uses K[1] for the integration dummy variable (which I change \
to \[Rho] for better readability). In \[CapitalBeta](r), just above, \
Mathematica again uses the default dummy variable K[1]. This causes a \
programming problem here because \[CapitalBeta](\[Rho]) appears in \
\[GothicCapitalD](r) expression. When \[CapitalBeta](r) is plugged back into \
\[GothicCapitalD](r), the \[GothicCapitalD](r) expression will contain a \
double integral and Mathematica will use K[1] for both dummy variables of \
integration.\"\>"], "Print",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.98053510835133*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "During evaluation of \
In[16561]:=",ExpressionUUID->"16aeac27-ef3f-44d5-9c53-cfe4a16825fb"],

Cell[BoxData["\<\"It is necesary to override the Mathematica default and make \
one of the dummy variables K[2]. For programming, it turns out to be easiest \
to just assign K[2] to the first function, \[GothicCapitalD](r), and then let \
the Mathematica assign the default K[1] to the second function, \
\[CapitalBeta](r).\"\>"], "Print",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.980535108352034*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "During evaluation of \
In[16561]:=",ExpressionUUID->"999faed9-cbf3-4c58-aaad-253ae5c1a522"],

Cell[BoxData["\<\"Further note: When an expression has just a single integral \
of r, I dispaly \[Rho] as the dummy variable. When there is a double integral \
of r, I display \[Sigma] as the inner dummy variable of integration and \
\[Rho] as the outer dummy variable.\"\>"], "Print",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.980535108352631*^9},
 CellLabel->
  "During evaluation of \
In[16561]:=",ExpressionUUID->"47f2bd58-e98f-4b3b-8fa1-9ff4fbd58b74"],

